ne 1550","1549":"1549","Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England":"Kidderminster St Mary, Worcestershire, England","Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England, Kingdom of England":"Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Hartpury,Gloucester,England":"Hartpury, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bowyer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a maker or seller of bows, or an archer, from Middle English <i>bowyere</i>, an agent derivative of Old English <i>boga</i> ‘bow’. Compare   Bowman  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bowman","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for an archer, hunter or soldier armed with a bow, from Middle English <i>bow(e)man</i>, <i>bouman</i> (from Old English <i>boga</i> ‘bow’ + <i>mann</i> ‘man’). This word was distinguished from   Bowyer  , which denoted a maker or seller of bows.","Americanized form of German   Baumann   or the Dutch cognate   Bouwman  ."]},{"name":"Bouyer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Frederique, Monique, Napoleon.","English: variant of   Bowyer  .","French (southern): regional variant of   Bouvier  . Compare   Beyea  ."]},{"name":"Boyers","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Bowyer  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":24,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":33,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":44,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":62,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":75,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":95,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705213,"age":117,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Bowyer was born in 1525, in Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England. He married Joane Holyday in Hartpury, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 3 daughters."},"et":{"1525–":"1525–Surnud","1535–1556":"1535–1556","1546–Female":"1546–Surnud","1549–1549":"1549–1549","1550–Male":"1550–Surnud","1550–1609":"1550–1609","1550–Female":"1550–Surnud","1556–1686":"1556–1686","–Unknown":"Surnud","1525–Male":"1525–Surnud","29 May 1549":"29. mai 1549","1550":"1550","1525":"1525","25 January 1546":"25. jaanuar 1546","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1546":"1546","1535":"1535","1556":"1556","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1686":"1686","1651":"1651","1609":"1609","about 1550":"umbes 1550","16 June 1550":"16. juuni 1550","1549":"1549","Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England":"Kiddermi